SIMPLE: shave
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shave
<hw>Shave</hw> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧v)</pr>, <def><pos>obs. p. p.</pos> of
<er>Shave</er>.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His beard was <qex>shave</qex> as nigh as ever he can.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shave
<hw>Shave</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Shaved</conjf> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧vd)</pr>;<pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shaved</conjf> or <conjf>Shaven</conjf> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧v"'n)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Shaving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>shaven</ets>, <ets>schaven</ets>, AS. <ets>scafan</ets>,
<ets>sceafan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>schaven</ets>, G.
<ets>schaben</ets>, Icel. <ets>skafa</ets>, Sw. <ets>skafva</ets>, Dan.
<ets>skave</ets>, Goth. <ets>scaban</ets>, Russ. <ets>kopate</ets> to
dig, Gr. <grk>ska`ptein</grk>, and probably to L. <ets>scabere</ets> to
scratch, to scrape. Cf. <er>Scab</er>, <er>Shaft</er>,
<er>Shape</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut or pare off from the
surface of a body with a razor or other edged instrument; to cut off
closely, as with a razor; <as>as, to <ex>shave</ex> the
beard</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make bare or smooth by cutting off closely the
surface, or surface covering, of; especially, to remove the hair from
with a razor or other sharp instrument; to take off the beard or hair
of; <as>as, to <ex>shave</ex> the face or the crown of the head; he
<ex>shaved</ex> himself.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll <qex>shave</qex> your crown for this.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laborer with the bending scythe is seen⟦br⟧
<qex>Shaving</qex> the surface of the waving green.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cut off thin slices from; to cut in thin
slices.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plants bruised or <qex>shaven</qex> in leaf or root.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To skim along or near the surface of; to pass close
to, or touch lightly, in passing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now <qex>shaves</qex> with level wing the deep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To strip; to plunder; to fleece.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shave a note</b></col>, <cd>to buy it at a discount
greater than the legal rate of interest, or to deduct in discounting it
more than the legal rate allows.</cd> <mark>[Cant, U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1325 --></p>

<p><ent>Shave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shave
<hw>Shave</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To use a razor for
removing the beard; to cut closely; hence, to be hard and severe in a
bargain; to practice extortion; to cheat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shave
<hw>Shave</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>scafa</ets>,
sceafa, a sort of knife. See <er>Shave</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A thin slice; a shaving.</def>
<rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cutting of the beard; the operation of
shaving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An exorbitant discount on a note.</def>
<mark>[Cant, U.S.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A premium paid for an
extension of the time of delivery or payment, or for the right to vary a
stock contract in any particular.</def> <mark>[Cant, U.S.]</mark>
<rj><au>N. Biddle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A hand tool consisting of a sharp blade with a
handle at each end; a drawing knife; a spokeshave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The act of passing very near to, so as almost to
graze; <as>as, the bullet missed by a close <ex>shave</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shave grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the scouring
rush. See the Note under <er>Equisetum</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Shave
hook</b></col>, <cd>a tool for scraping metals, consisting of a
sharp-edged triangular steel plate attached to a shank and
handle.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shaveling</ent>⟦br⟧
